Happy Tuesday, crafty friends! I hope you had a great start to your week. Today I'm sharing this beautiful Poppy Mix card featuring new products from the @pinkfreshstudio December 2022 release. Before I get to my card, I have to tell you the cutest story about my mama, @ladycrippen.

If you haven't heard yet, we are moving back to my home state of Montana next year. According to the builder, our house will be finished sometime between June-September. We are moving to the small town of Anaconda, MT, which is where my mom lives too. Population 8,000 and 20 miles away from Georgetown Lake, which we fell in love with this past summer! Currently Anaconda looks like it's straight out of a Hallmark movie, and I am SO excited to be part of all the festivities next year. They create an ice skating rink around the town Christmas tree....I mean, come on! How cute is that?!

Anyways...I had been raving about that since last week when I found out. My mama called me one night and said, "I've got something to tell you that is really going to sell you even further on Anaconda. I just went to the new wine bar in town, and it is fantastic. The owners are so nice, and they've got so many craft beers available that Josh will enjoy too. And once they get going they are planning on having wine tastings, classes and brunches on Sunday." Isn't she the cutest?! Lol! We've signed the paperwork on the house, so it's practically a done deal...but I love that she is excited and also trying to keep us excited as well. (I don't think you could keep me from being excited...I am SO HAPPY to be going home.) Anyways...just a cute little story I wanted to share today!

You can get all the details about my card today over on my blog...I hope you'll check it out!

There are a couple ways that I use my @tim_holtz travel glass mat from @tonicstudios. Of course I take it with me to craft days with friends & such and use it as my ink blending surface. But it gets WAY more use as a base for this fun stamping hack! We offer a lot of 4x12 stamp sets at @pinkfreshstudio, and some of them do not fit inside a standard stamping platform. But by taping the platform down to the travel glass mat, I can use the outside of the lid to stamp, which is a much bigger surface. You can still double stamp because the platform is taped into place, and your cardstock is taped down to the other side of the glass mat.

When we have washi tape releases, or I know that I'm going to be creating with multiple slimline sets...I will leave this set up as is so that it is ready to go when I need it! I love that my travel glass mat gets far more use than just for portability purposes these days. This Tonic Travel Glass Mat is currently on sale for 50% off at @scrapbookcom, so it's a perfect time to grab one if this stamping hack would be useful to you! I'll link to it in my profile and in my Stories shortly. I hope you have an awesome Thursday!

Happy Monday, crafty friends! I've got another Valentine's day card to share with you today that I made live on my personal YouTube channel two Sundays ago! It features the new Floral Border product suite from @pinkfreshstudio, along with our Jeff Alpha & Phrase Builder: Happy sets.

I love the Floral Border design because it allows me to perfectly use the standard foiled and solid foiled versions together! Sometimes the solid foiled versions are a little too bold for me, but I really love to use them behind things just to peek out and add interest. By flipping the ink blended version 180 degrees over top of the solid foiled, it allows it too peek through from underneath while keeping a more subtle feel.

Happy Wednesday, crafty friends! First off, thank you so much for all your kind comments on yesterday's post. I appreciate them more than words can express, and I am so thankful for our little community.

Today I've got another card to share with you featuring the new In Bloom & Everyday Sentiments die sets from @teamspellbinders. These are from the Metamorphosis collection by @inklipse. Don't you just love these chunky flowers?! I've combined these die sets with the Crossed Lines hot foil plate, and I think they are a perfect match!

Let's talk about solid foiling, because it's not a perfect science! When I did the reverse foiling on this one, I did a really bad job of lining the design up with on the solid plate. It was a tad off center, which was a tad annoying to me. Lol! But if you know me at all, you know I don't like to waste things or time. So I held on to it to see if I could use it at some point in the future.

When I assembled the In Blooms florals, it popped into my head that this set might be perfect...and it definitely is! I skewed the entire card design to help hide that I had foiled it a little off, and I don't think you can really tell! My advice is to not toss something just because it didn't finish perfectly. Hold on to it, or look at it and see if you can find a way to hide the mistake or flaw. I LOVE how this card turned out, and it wouldn't have happened if I had tossed my mistake!

If you want more details about this card, you can get them over on my blog. Have a great day!

I was resistant to trying this for some reason, but @houses_built_of_cards wore me down and I finally did it. Lol! I can fully admit to just being stubborn, because cutting intricate dies with bubble mailers as the shim is about the best thing ever. It puts less wear & tear on your plates and machines than a metal shim, and it makes removing chads SO EASY. A lot of them will actually stay on the mailer, but if they don't, they are really easy to poke out.

I used a plastic bubble mailer in today's video, but I've found that the chads seem to stay behind in the paper bubble mailers better. Either way, both work wonderfully! One more tip - if you want to add a decorative edge like this directly to your card front...be sure to score and fold your card first. I've tried it both ways, and it's really hard to fold correctly if you do the diecutting first. I hope that by sharing my experiences, I can make crafting easier for you! Lol! ;)

These cards are up on my blog today if you'd like to get more info on them. I hope you'll check it out!

I was gifted a Gemini II from my friend Kimberly Saldaña at the Simon Says Stamp CREATE event this past spring. To say that I was surprised would be an understatement, as I just don't ever expect anything like that. I am so grateful for the gift, and recently was able to get new plates for it and all set up in my craft studio! After using it to cut out a few things, I noticed that the suggested diecutting sandwich was just a bit too much pressure for my dies. I took a look in the manual, and it specifically states to try various shim combinations when using a new die for the first time to find the right fit.

Here is what I found works best for me - I've removed the magnetic shim, and replaced it with a 130 LB paper shim. Sometimes I can even take that paper shim out, and still have enough pressure. I think this is such valuable information and I'm so happy I thought to look in the manual, because dies are not produced exactly the same, and over time, pressure can change in machines based on age, usage & more. If you aren't happy with your diecutting results, take a look at your sandwich and see what changes you can make in order to be more successful! I think this advice is sound for any diecut machine you might be using.

P.S. I am loving the new Gemini II! If you have any questions, I'll try to answer them!

7 years. I will never forget you. I will never forget that you existed. That you left a mark on this world. A mark on my heart so big that some days I don't know how I continue surviving the loss of you. Of your sister.

But I do. Every single day I survive you & Ellie. Because there is no other choice. Because in the cruelest way, life is still beautiful & worthwhile. And you both deserve a mom who truly lives, despite the pain of loss that can bring me to my knees.

I love you and miss you both every single second of every single day, Layton Caleb and Ellie Grace. 🐻💔

Yesterday was a dark day. The anniversary of Layton's death is always my worst, most triggering day of the year. It became further compounded two years ago when I lost my sweet grandma on the same day. Yesterday I felt myself falling into that pit of despair that most days I keep at bay, and this year I just needed to sit there. The thing about darkness? It's always followed by light. It's one of the most beautiful parts of life. I'm not miraculously healed. I don't miraculously feel better. I can just see the light today, when I couldn't yesterday.

Part of that is because you, as a collective community & individually, poured your love & light into me. You lifted me up when I couldn't do it for myself, you spoke the names of my children, and held space when I needed it most. There aren't words that can express my gratitude for that. All I can say is thank you. From the very depths of my heart...thank you. 🤍

Thanksgiving can be very nuanced for me, as I know it can be for many. I have so much to be thankful for, but I am acutely aware of the empty chairs at my dinner table and the holes in my heart that losing Ellie & Layton has left.

This summer I told you that we terminated the contract on the home in Montana that we were supposed to be moving into this past September. Instead, we closed on a piece of land in September. It's in the exact location in Montana that we wanted to be, and it's 100% ours. The bank doesn't own it - we do. Only our names are on the deed, which I am so very thankful for.

Our plan is to build on it in 2025 as we need some time to replenish our savings. We have a tentative home design that we will work with our builder to make some changes, making it exactly what we want and a home we can age with. And yes - we are 99.99% sure we have picked a builder. Which is probably the most stressful part for us, considering the fiasco we went through with the first one.

I realize that I am incredibly lucky to own land in Montana. It's a tiny piece of land, but it's still our piece of Montana. My dream of going home starts now....🤍🤍

Happy Friday, crafty friends! Do you love embossing folders? I've got a quick tip for you if you do! After you've dry embossed your paper panel and removed it from the embossing folder, flip it over and look at both sides. More often than not, I prefer the look of the debossed side...which I featured on both of my projects today!

I also have a foiling tip to share as well! Do you have photo paper in your office that isn't being used? Try foiling sentiments or anything that you don't plan to ink blend or color to it. It gives practically perfect results every time, and the gloss on the paper really makes the foiling pop! You can also use Yupo paper, or the specialty Glimmer foiling paper from Spellbinders - they have some similarities to glossy photo paper. You will likely want to add another cardstock layer underneath, as this type of paper is typically a pretty low weight. I used one layer of 130 LB cardstock underneath mine, and they were PERFECT!
